segments.text: I'm walking on, I'm walking on the Philopappou Hill. It's sunny today, February, we are in Athens, Greece, feels a bit like spring, we have a lot of the early wild flowers out, I don't know the names here yet, they are like different yellows,
there is some white, purple, the butterflies are starting to fly around, they are quite small at this time, they are white.

I'm walking on the same path as I took Laurel and Elliott when they were visiting Athens in November, it's part of the hill that is facing towards our house, walking towards the Acropolis, which is only a few minutes away from where we live.
I come here quite often, in times of the year I come here every single day of the year, it's a nature spot in the middle of Athens and a place that I bring my son Uno to play.

It's a dog walker, I guess it's a freelancers and dog walkers that you find at this time of the day, it's 10:50 in the morning, AM, just past the area where Uno and I would make a dent with scrape branches and stuff like that.
It was a big project last year but we haven't been doing it so much over the winter, but maybe now when it's getting warmer we can soon do it again.
I really enjoy all the repetitions that comes along with parenting, doing the same things again and again and always with equal excitement.

It's very inspiring for how I do work in general, instead of having to do new things in new ways, I also just honor the things that I like to do and just keep doing it, like walking this walk and watching the butterflies here.
There are two that are kind of dancing together, it's quite beautiful.
Soon I'm going to be up at the area where you look at the house with domes on top.
It's funny because Laurel writes a news letter inspired by domes, from dome to dome, another day in the dome.
I feel like spring is quite a hopeful season.
See all the plants wanting to get out and shine and get attention, catch the bees or whatever they are up to.
Everything is green at this time of the year, like saturated green, like an iPhone photo.
Soon it's going to be warm, very warm and the color will fade in and the youngsters will be more soft.
I like that time a lot too.
Now I can see the Aegean Sea over to Agina Island, not so far away from Athens.
Soon I will be able to have a look at Acropolis.
It's really strange to live in such a vicinity, a symbol of modern democracy.
I'm trying to catch up on the histories and the cultural significance of Acropolis since we moved here.
It's still a lot to learn.
It feels like with every step I take it's just even more that is relevant to discover.
Sometimes I find daunting, the feeling of not being able to finish it.
Not being able to know everything around why Acropolis exists and how it shaped and still shapes culture.
I'm also reaching a point where I really enjoy that everything is so much larger and faster and ever-evolving than myself.
Spring becomes summer ... becomes winter, and at least if you're in a certain climate, others are a little bit less.
I like the circularity of life that doesn't really go anywhere, even though it goes in constant motion.
Things are different, things are not different, but it's alive.
It's pleasant to see how things get reinterpreted, rewritten, and how humans are able to find so deep meaning in symbols and relationships and artifacts.
How they travel great distances for love, or for ambition or desire.
Now I see Acropolis and I see a butterfly and I will say bye-bye.
